Yes, I know I'm necroposting. Actually I'm necroposting on a response to a necropost of a necropost. But I have some things to say that may interest people today so I'm gonna say it. Real life MD/PhD neuroscientist here, specifically molecular biology of stress and the serotonin system. There is no dose of an SSRI (or SNRI), or non-selective SRI/NRI that will produce a large enough effect ot come close. They just don't attenuate severe acute stimulus driven fear enough. You might be able to do it with a benzodiazepine, but you'd probably be close to unconscious if not unconscious . You wouldn't remember much if anything that's for sure.

Three words: bilateral amygdala lesions.

+Show

-Hide


Bilateral amygdala lesions decease (if partial) or eliminate )(if complete) the ability to experience fear. Complete bilateral congenital absence of the amygdala results in essentially compete absence of fear. this:

One major exception CO2 inhalation will still produce panic even without amygdale, sometimes causing people to experience fear for the first time in their lives. (disclosure, I got my degrees where this work was done and have some professional connections with a couple of the authors)




On tryptophan and the othet aromatic amino acids

+Show

-Hide


Tryptophan is the ammo acid that serotonin and melatonin are made from, just as tyrosine is the amino acid that norepinephrine, dopamine, and epinephrine and melanin) are made from. Humans can synthesize tryrosine from phenylalanine but phenylalanine and tryptophan must be obtained fron the diet. The casein in (the inaptly named) non-diary creamer is high in all 3 of these amino acids.










